<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910724-0124</DOCNO><DOCID>910724-0124.</DOCID><HL>   CIA Director to Postpone   Retirement for a Month</HL><DATE>07/24/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A12</SO><GV>CONGRESS (CNG)EXECUTIVE (EXE)</GV><RE>NORTH AMERICA (NME)UNITED STATES (US)</RE><LP>   WASHINGTON -- At President Bush's request, William Websterhas agreed to stay an additional month as director of theCentral Intelligence Agency.   Mr. Webster, who had planned to retire from the CIA at theend of this month, was asked to stay because the Senate hasput off action on the nomination of Robert Gates to becomethe new head of the CIA. Confirmation hearings have beendelayed until Sept. 16, while the Senate IntelligenceCommittee tries to determine more precisely what informationMr. Gates had about the Iran-Contra scandal.</LP><TEXT>   In addition to announcing Mr. Webster's decision, theWhite House said Mr. Bush made another impassioned defense ofMr. Gates and indicated the president will stick by him.   At a meeting of his cabinet, Mr. Bush expressed his&quot;personal outrage&quot; at the controversy surrounding Mr. Gates,White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said. Mr. Bushstressed &quot;how much he supports him,&quot; the spokesman said.</TEXT></DOC>